<chapter subject="Physics" id="1" name="Physical World">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Physics is the study of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nature and natural phenomena</option><option id="B">Chemical reactions</option><option id="C">Society</option><option id="D">History</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physics is fundamental science of nature.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following is a fundamental force in nature?</text>
            <option id="A">Gravitational force</option><option id="B">Friction</option><option id="C">Viscous force</option><option id="D">Tension</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gravitation is one of the four fundamental forces.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The weakest fundamental force is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gravitational force</option><option id="B">Electromagnetic force</option><option id="C">Strong nuclear force</option><option id="D">Weak nuclear force</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Despite its large scale impact, it is the weakest.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The strongest fundamental force is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Strong nuclear force</option><option id="B">Gravitational force</option><option id="C">Electromagnetic force</option><option id="D">Weak nuclear force</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Strongest force acts inside the nucleus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Newton's law of gravitation is a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Universal law</option><option id="B">Local law</option><option id="C">Chemical law</option><option id="D">Temporary law</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Applies everywhere in the universe.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The scientist who discovered the law of planetary motion is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kepler</option><option id="B">Newton</option><option id="C">Einstein</option><option id="D">Galileo</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Kepler's three laws of planetary motion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>The 'Scientific Method' involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Systematic observations and experiments</option><option id="B">Guesswork only</option><option id="C">Ancient myths</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on evidence and verification.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unification in physics means ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Explaining diverse phenomena with few laws</option><option id="B">Breaking things down</option><option id="C">Ignoring data</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Goal of physics is simplicity and unity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Reductionism in physics involves ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Explaining complex systems from simpler parts</option><option id="B">Making things bigger</option><option id="C">Combining all forces</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived properties from basic components.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Nuclear force only acts over ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Very short distances (10^-15 m)</option><option id="B">Long distances</option><option id="C">Infinite distance</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Short range force.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which force binds electrons to the nucleus?</text>
            <option id="A">Electromagnetic force</option><option id="B">Gravitational force</option><option id="C">Strong nuclear</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Electrostatic attraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Gravity is always ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Attractive</option><option id="B">Repulsive</option><option id="C">Both</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Never found to be repulsive.</explanation>
        </question>
