            <option id="A">W and Z bosons</option><option id="B">Photons</option><option id="C">Gluons</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heavy intermediate vector bosons.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which symmetry is broken in weak interactions related to time?</text>
            <option id="A">T-symmetry (but usually CP is the famous one)</option><option id="B">Parity</option><option id="C">Charge</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>CP violation discovered in K-meson decay.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard Model of particle physics misses which force?</text>
            <option id="A">Gravity</option><option id="B">Weak</option><option id="C">Strong</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gravity is not yet fully integrated into SM.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>A physical law is 'elegant' if it is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Brief and Powerful</option><option id="B">Long and complex</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aesthetic value in physics.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conservation of linear momentum for a system requires ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero net external force</option><option id="B">Zero internal force</option><option id="C">Constant velocity of each</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Law consequence of N2L.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conservation of angular momentum requires ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero net external torque</option><option id="B">Zero net force</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>τ = dL/dt.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which particle is its own anti-particle?</text>
            <option id="A">Photon</option><option id="B">Electron</option><option id="C">Proton</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Charge zero, real vector field.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Antimatter was predicted by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Paul Dirac</option><option id="B">Feynman</option><option id="C">Einstein</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From Dirac Equation solutions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Technological application: MRI works on principle of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nuclear Magnetic Resonance (NMR)</option><option id="B">Refraction</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physics contribution to medicine.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Semiconductors were explained by ____ theory.</text>
            <option id="A">Energy Band Theory</option><option id="B">Classical flow</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Quantum mechanics application to solids.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Superconductivity is loss of resistance at ____ temperatures.</text>
            <option id="A">Cryogenic / Very low</option><option id="B">Very high</option><option id="C">Room</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Meissner effect related.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Higgs Boson gives ____ to elementary particles.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass</option><option id="B">Charge</option><option id="C">Spin</option><option id="D">Color</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>'God Particle' in popular media.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>CERN is located in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Switzerland/France</option><option id="B">USA</option><option id="C">India</option><option id="D">Japan</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Home of LHC.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dark Matter is suspected to cause ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Missing mass for galaxy rotation curves</option><option id="B">Light emission</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unknown form of matter.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Dark Energy is responsible for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Accelerated expansion of universe</option><option id="B">Gravity</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Counteracts gravity on cosmic scale.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Big Bang was not an explosion IN space, but OF ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Space-time itself</option><option id="B">A giant star</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cosmological expansion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Singularity is a point of ____ density.</text>
            <option id="A">Infinite</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">Medium</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Laws of physics break down.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Black holes were theoretically derived from ____ field equations.</text>
            <option id="A">Schwarzschild solution of Einstein</option><option id="B">Newton</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Event horizon concept.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hawking radiation suggests black holes can ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Evaporate</option><option id="B">Exist forever</option><option id="C">Grow only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Quantum effect near event horizon.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Unification of electricity and magnetism by Maxwell required ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Displacement current</option><option id="B">More batteries</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Gap in Ampere's law fixed.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Who proposed wave-nature of matter?</text>
            <option id="A">De Broglie</option><option id="B">Bohr</option><option id="C">Hertz</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>λ = h/p.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
